There are many ways.

33
0:01:29,740000 --> 0:01:34,660000
When you invite people to visualize with you, to co-create what you're actually doing, and

34
0:01:34,660000 --> 0:01:40,860000
this is the first of many visual metaphors to come, you're sort of laying out a mini

35
0:01:40,860000 --> 0:01:49,760000
red carpet to invite them to shine. It's also a red thread that the conversation has

36
0:01:49,760000 --> 0:01:56
when you invite others to visualize with you. So what I'd like to share in the next five to six

37
0:01:56,000000 --> 0:01:56,990000
minutes with you are three practices that help you to invite others to visualize together.

38
0:02:03,700000 --> 0:02:08,740000
But first, can I take you back just a minute to my very first high-stakes presentation,

39
0:02:08,740000 --> 0:02:15,020000
not as a university professor, but in my former life as a consultant.

40
0:02:15,020000 --> 0:02:19,160000
Client had asked us to analyze if they should enter a new multi-billion market.

41
0:02:19,160000 --> 0:02:26,160000
And we worked very hard to analyze this market, and I had produced about 40 data-driven slides to show the client that

42
0:02:26,160000 --> 0:02:32,640000
we had worked hard and that he should not enter this business. Just as I was ready to go and

43
0:02:32,640000 --> 0:02:39,600000
bombard the client with those slides, my then boss said, Martin, take a seat, hold your horses.

44
0:02:40,480000 --> 0:02:46,880000
And instead of me going through the slides, he showed the perplexed audience one sketch,

45
0:02:46,880000 --> 0:02:50
one visual metaphor, and it was this one.

46
0:02:50,000000 --> 0:02:50,990000
It was a fortress built on sand.

47
0:02:54,000000 --> 0:02:54,990000
This guy had just summarized all of my 40 slides in a single image

48
0:02:58,480000 --> 0:02:59,680000
because he was right.

49
0:02:59,680000 --> 0:03:02,520000
This new market was like a fortress,

50
0:03:02,520000 --> 0:03:05,720000
very hard to conquer because of patent shields, economies

51
0:03:05,720000 --> 0:03:07,560000
of scale contracts.

52
0:03:07,560000 --> 0:03:12,520000
It was not even worth conquering, it was sinking into the sand so to speak, because the technology

53
0:03:12,520000 --> 0:03:15,540000
was being replaced by another one.

54
0:03:15,540000 --> 0:03:19,340000
And of course the client then asked about details like the patent analysis I had done

55
0:03:19,340000 --> 0:03:48,340000
or the contracts and so forth, and I could show finally my slide with that analysis. But this leading with a visual metaphor really changed the dynamics of the conversation. It was much more collaborative. First the overview with this visual metaphor and then the details on demand. And I realized it's all about a conversation. It's much better this way. When you first show overview with the help of a metaphor that by the way the client picked up and used also verbally.

56
0:03:48,340000 --> 0:03:50,840000
And that got me thinking as a researcher.

57
0:03:50,840000 --> 0:03:55,560000
And in many experiments with managers and students we found three practices that I want

58
0:03:55,560000 --> 0:04:06,860000
to share with you that you can use to really reap the power of pictures professionally, and the first one might shock you, especially the design

59
0:04:06,860000 --> 0:04:11,080000
aficionados among you.

60
0:04:11,080000 --> 0:04:17,380000
If you want visualization, graphic representations to work for you and for collaboration, make

61
0:04:17,380000 --> 0:04:20,820000
them ugly.

62
0:04:20,820000 --> 0:04:22,680000
Beauty is the enemy of collaboration.

63
0:04:22,680000 --> 0:04:28,920000
If something looks too nice, it looks like it doesn't need revision or improvement. I call this the museum effect.

64
0:04:28,920000 --> 0:04:31,920000
People just stare and say, yeah, that looks perfect.

65
0:04:31,920000 --> 0:04:35,240000
And the thinking stops there. So you want to

66
0:04:35,240000 --> 0:04:39,640000
use the power of provisionality. You want to signal with your drawings

67
0:04:39,640000 --> 0:04:43,680000
this is work in progress and invite collaboration in this way. So this is

68
0:04:43,680000 --> 0:04:47,320000
good news for all of us who are terrible at drawing.

69
0:04:47,320000 --> 0:04:49,900000
So it's not a bug, it's a feature.

70
0:04:49,900000 --> 0:04:54,880000
The technical term is low perceived finishness.

71
0:04:54,880000 --> 0:04:56,320000
It looks provisional.

72
0:04:56,320000 --> 0:04:58,660000
It invites collaboration.

73
0:04:58,660000 --> 0:05:04,120000
And by the way, banks and telecom companies and insurances have been using this all along.

74
0:05:04,120000 --> 0:05:05,200000
It's called pencil selling.

75
0:05:06,040000 --> 0:05:08,180000
When instead of using shiny slides,

76
0:05:08,280000 --> 0:05:11,820000
you just sketch something with a pencil for a client, like a product.

77
0:05:12,520000 --> 0:05:15,900000
In our experiments, we were able to show this actually is much better.

78
0:05:16,000000 --> 0:05:16,990000
It leads to more sales.

79
0:05:17,300000 --> 0:05:20,680000
So if you want to harness the power of visualization for collaboration,

80
0:05:21,300000 --> 0:05:22,360000
make them look ugly.

81
0:05:22,880000 --> 0:05:24,180000
Make them look provisional.

82
0:05:24,300000 --> 0:05:26,160000
Use sketches and doodles.

83
0:05:26,160000 --> 0:05:31,440000
We've shown in our experiments even little tweaks to software to make it look more sketchy

84
0:05:31,440000 --> 0:05:37,720000
boosts collaboration and creativity. And this brings me to the second advice I'd like to

85
0:05:37,720000 --> 0:05:46,380000
share with you. Like my boss, lead with visual metaphors. Don't just use diagrams, although they are powerful,

86
0:05:46,380000 --> 0:05:54,920000
or charts or maps. Visual metaphors are magical. They access what people already know. They

87
0:05:54,920000 --> 0:06:01,420000
bring out new solution ideas. They make things much more concrete, like a mini red carpet

88
0:06:01,420000 --> 0:06:08,860000
or a red thread. Let me give you an example. In a study that we originally did for BMW Financial Services and then published, we

89
0:06:08,860000 --> 0:06:17,640000
used the identical strategy of BMW and communicated it to different staff members, groups.

90
0:06:17,640000 --> 0:06:22,360000
Once we used standard bullet point slides, then we used a diagram.

91
0:06:22,360000 --> 0:06:26,160000
And for the third group, we used the mountain trail visual metaphor

92
0:06:26,160000 --> 0:06:28,920000
with the same content as the other two.

93
0:06:28,920000 --> 0:06:30,560000
And guess what?

94
0:06:30,560000 --> 0:06:35,080000
For the group where we visualized through the mountain trail the strategy,

95
0:06:35,080000 --> 0:06:39,280000
not only did they remember a lot more later on,

96
0:06:39,280000 --> 0:06:44
they were also much more motivated to implement the strategy.

97
0:06:44,000000 --> 0:06:44,990000
Now, I've never met a metaphor I didn't like,

98
0:06:46,720000 --> 0:06:52,480000
but clearly not all metaphors are equally well suited. You want to make sure that the metaphor

99
0:06:52,480000 --> 0:06:56,960000
is simpler than what you're trying to explain, that it's concrete and that people have a

100
0:06:56,960000 --> 0:07:00,800000
connection with it. And that is hopefully the right connection. I will never use again

101
0:07:01,360000 --> 0:07:07,880000
the volcano metaphor as I did once for creativity in a country that is at risk of active volcanoes.

102
0:07:07,880000 --> 0:07:11,520000
So choose your metaphors well, and if you do that,

103
0:07:11,520000 --> 0:07:15,520000
then it will resonate with people, it will be much more memorable,

104
0:07:15,520000 --> 0:07:18,720000
it sticks like a red ribbon on the floor.

105
0:07:18,720000 --> 0:07:22,560000
Here's another example of such a visual metaphor.

106
0:07:22,560000 --> 0:07:27,120000
It can come from nature, it can come from technology, it can come from mythology, you name it.

107
0:07:27,120000 --> 0:07:30,600000
Here, I used the bridge to visualize a few,

108
0:07:30,600000 --> 0:07:32,720000
I'm a professor of communications management,

109
0:07:32,720000 --> 0:07:35,600000
a few communication problems.

110
0:07:35,600000 --> 0:07:38,220000
And so it's simple, also visually,

111
0:07:38,220000 --> 0:07:42,680000
and the beauty of this kind of visual,

112
0:07:42,680000 --> 0:07:44,800000
we can learn that from comic strips,

113
0:07:44,800000 --> 0:07:49,240000
is that it starts a series that people then want to complete.

114
0:07:49,240000 --> 0:07:51,760000
And I think that's very powerful in collaboration.

115
0:07:51,760000 --> 0:07:56,040000
I call this third practice that I want to share with you in conclusion,

116
0:07:56,040000 --> 0:07:59,080000
I call this visual variation.

117
0:07:59,080000 --> 0:08:02,600000
You use a metaphor or a diagram, and then you vary it.

118
0:08:02,600000 --> 0:08:05,880000
You repeat it, but slightly differently. And the magic

119
0:08:05,880000 --> 0:08:10,580000
that this does for collaboration is people start to extend the series you're giving them. So for

120
0:08:10,580000 --> 0:08:17,220000
example here, communication is one-sided because of a lack of listening, right? One-way street or

121
0:08:17,220000 --> 0:08:23,160000
the bridge is not aligned, there's misunderstandings or it's too full, the too many messages crowd out

122
0:08:23,160000 --> 0:08:27,320000
the key message, and people automatically think of other communication problems

123
0:08:27,320000 --> 0:08:28,920000
through the metaphor of the bridge,

124
0:08:28,920000 --> 0:08:31,240000
like one car going off the bridge,

125
0:08:31,240000 --> 0:08:33,960000
maybe because the person is too emotional, right?

126
0:08:33,960000 --> 0:08:35,280000
Or the bridge being shaky,

127
0:08:35,280000 --> 0:08:38,360000
maybe because there is no trust in the relationship.

128
0:08:38,360000 --> 0:08:42,040000
Visual metaphors spark the imagination,

129
0:08:42,040000 --> 0:08:48,280000
especially if they come in a series of images. This is by the way

130
0:08:48,280000 --> 0:08:55,040000
a very empirically validated theory, it's called variation theory, and it basically

131
0:08:55,040000 --> 0:09:00,460000
says that you do not understand anything until you understand it in more than one

132
0:09:00,460000 --> 0:09:07,120000
way. And so if you ask me for advice how to make visuals more part of your everyday work, I

133
0:09:07,120000 --> 0:09:11,920000
would say start a series, start a simple image, it doesn't have to be sophisticated, and invite

134
0:09:11,920000 --> 0:09:15,100000
others to build on that.

135
0:09:15,100000 --> 0:09:18,080000
Here is my final example for that.

136
0:09:18,080000 --> 0:09:22,440000
As university professors, we often advise students, and many of our students still have

137
0:09:22,440000 --> 0:09:25,520000
this stereotypical career path in mind

138
0:09:25,520000 --> 0:09:29,220000
that it only goes upward in terms of salary or hierarchy.

139
0:09:29,360000 --> 0:09:34,380000
And I drew this visual variation to invite them to think about alternative career trajectories.

140
0:09:34,500000 --> 0:09:36,300000
So the career doesn't have to be linear.

141
0:09:36,440000 --> 0:09:39,420000
In fact, I find, I don't know how about you,

142
0:09:40,000000 --> 0:09:40,990000
that the most intriguing careers are often non-linear,

143
0:09:44,780000 --> 0:09:48,720000
are different than this upward staircase model.

144
0:09:49,840000 --> 0:09:53,800000
So in conclusion, go forth and visualize or vanish,

145
0:09:53,800000 --> 0:09:55,640000
use the power of pictures,

146
0:09:55,640000 --> 0:09:58,400000
and when you do that, you will see it boosts your creativity,

147
0:09:58,400000 --> 0:09:59,520000
it improves decisions,

148
0:09:59,520000 --> 0:10:04,280000
especially if you use images that signal that they are a work in progress,

149
0:10:04,280000 --> 0:10:09,320000
that invite others, like a red carpet to shine together,

150
0:10:09,320000 --> 0:10:12,320000
to co-create something new together.

151
0:10:13,120000 --> 0:10:17,640000
Especially if you don't just rely on abstract diagrams or charts,

152
0:10:17,640000 --> 0:10:22,560000
but use the power of visual metaphors to activate what people already know.

153
0:10:22,560000 --> 0:10:25,720000
And thirdly, of course, if you don't just use a single image

154
0:10:25,720000 --> 0:10:28,680000
and overload that one, but start a sequence

155
0:10:28,680000 --> 0:10:30,940000
that your colleagues can build upon.

156
0:10:30,940000 --> 0:10:32,240000
Thank you very much.
